 reasonable rate; all of which is the standard norm for Early Access games with a small team.  Its just himself & I think maybe he collaborates with 1 or 2 others.  Rinse, repeat; its an ongoing process, but one which the Dev has continued to see through on an acceptable basis.Aside from his normal To-Do list & agenda of updating & progressing the game over time in his own visions, hes also been receptive to the posts people have made with bugs/suggestions, etc; as evidenced by the past posts from myself & others here & the change-logs & resulting game-play changes that followed.At one point, due to having a vested interest in this game; since its something very different & so nicely encompasses so many cool & different traits from other games & genres that I really like & since Ive always really hoped to see this game in completion someday; in my haste, I hadnt seen any Account activity or Discussion Forum posts from the Dev in about a month & a half, so was worried that the Dev might have gone bye-bye as too many of them far too often do, with EA games these days...but he promptly & politely responded, simply pointing out he always keeps a watchful eye, just not always from the Dev Account, which actually makes sense in hindsight.On that note, occasionally there will be the random/rare person that posts bugs/suggestions or w/e & then a week or 2 or more goes by without a response from the Dev & that person becomes upset or says stuff like, ""Oh the Dev must not care"". etc;  Which to be fair to them, up to a point, thats understandable.  I even jumped the gun myself once.  Its not unusual...& in fact is sadly half expected anymore with EA games, for the Dev to bail on a game, or just not be at all involved with the community.  But I can personally & honestly state, thats just not the case here, to this date.  He is just one guy & has his own personal RL stuff going on, just like many of us do & works on this game in his free time, which all things considered, seems like he must generally make a point to set most of it aside, to attend to this game.Also, he does personally respond to posts, just not every single one & not all day, every day.  I personally can relate to that, as Ive got a super busy schedule myself, sometimes too busy & have to prioritize the stuff I want to do VS the stuff I need to do, & even stopping all that to do something simple, like respond to a text or email, can add more to my plate then I can already handle at that time.  I think a lot of Devs here on Steam fit into that category, as most of them arent full time programmers/game-designers & their game isnt their main source of income.  Some Devs dont bother to read &/or respond to their customers ever, but this Dev does fairly often.  And to me, as long as that level of customer service/interaction continues & the game keeps moving forward in a positive direction as its been; thats all that matters to me & all I care about, to warrant supporting this or any Dev, that demonstrates that on-going level of commitment.Bugs:The last time Id put any time into this game was appx 2-3 months ago ( from time of this review @ Dec 17th 2016 ) & had been wanting to play the game again after the last few updates/bug fixes & try out the new DLC.So recently I was able to play several hours off & on over the last week.  Started a new game, after buying the new DLC.  Everything was running smooth & working great at first, with a few minor bugs like; every time saving & quitting then reloading save game, the same few tutorial help boxes popped up, like if youre starting a new game.  Or while paused, clicking expand land, you hear the SFX of game like it was running even though visually, the game still appeared paused.  Nothing big or game breaking at all.Some more problematic things started to occur later on tho, like upon saving & reloading, most NPCs were unhappy & leaving, with no indication there was a prob prior to saving & quitting.  To be fair, Dev has a thread stating if you have probs be sure to erase that data which Im not sure I did this last replay.http://steamcommunity.com/app/314240/discussions/0/35221584437504412/Despite any bugs or probs along the way, I have faith in this Dev, from his past actions, not just words & promises like some Devs can do.  My honest opinion is, if you like what you see advertised here from the games Vids & Description, then you cant go wrong buying this game.  Its pretty much exactly/mostly what youd want & expect from a game like this.  Its not however a super duper in-depth game.  And its not meant to be & doesnt have to be to still be fun & enjoyable.  Nor is it on the shallow end either.  Overall its more of a mid-depth semi-casual gaming experience with several aspects that are still nicely in-depth, with other aspects to still keep you on your toes & wanting to continue to play, manage, grow & expand your kingdom.Bottom line is, this games been in development for a while now & continues to progress steadily, considering its from an Inde Dev.  Depending on the current state of the game & where its at, you may experience a relatively bug-free game, or you may be in the middle of a recent content update with the inevitable bugs that follow, which TBH, yes can get frustrating.  But thinking about it... Why does one get frustrated with something in the first place, instead of just not even caring or thinking twice about it & instead just walk away?  Cuz you care about it.  Cuz you like it.  Cuz theres some part of you that has a vested interest in that thing to begin with lol.Which is ultimately a testament & compliment to RPG Tycoon & what it does right & why its worth most peoples time even now, & especially once its 100% finished.  And which is why Im still glad I bought this game, even tho it has some polishing to do yet & hopefully a few more features/game-play additions.  I look forward to the future when well see this game in its fully realized, finished state.  ( :"
