,Not Recommended,314240,26283819,"Posted: 28 October, 2016",all,Corpsing,"Final ThoughtsNot recommended.Game crashed before the tutorial was able to be completed. Occasional user interface (UI) elements persisted on the screen after a menu was closed, the only way to clear the screen was to quit the game and reload. Questing is tedious with a lack of polish to the interface. The hero management interface is broken and only half the intended features seem to work. The item systems is just barely working at this point resulting in game breaking bugs and lost inventory.IntroductionThis game is a unique twist on the classical RPG formula where instead of playing the hero, you manage their city. There are no monsters to battle, but you can train your heroes to improve their base statistics, solve quests to gain followers and cash. The ability to send multiple heroes in a party on epic quests is also fun. Sometimes a sub-quest involving the vanquishing of a villain appears or substantially better loot is to be had. The town has special buildings available once a certain level of experience is obtained.QuestingSending your heroes out on a quest involves a somewhat unique screen where you have to select six pieces of equipment they will take on their journey. This is interesting at first since each piece of equipment has a priority and some does nothing to assist the quest. As the heroes quest, more equipment and missions are unlocked. Once the equipment is placed in its correct priority slot, the mission results in better rewards. Unfortunately, the next time a hero goes on the same quest, this entire setup must be repeated. It gets tedious after a while since ultimately there are 30 different pieces of equipment available and the selection screen is limited to what it displays so there is a lot of scrolling involved. Understandably, the developers added a history screen and indicators to what equipment may be useful, though frustratingly they have this on a different ""history"" screen which causes a lot of back and fourth between the two windows.HeroesThe hero hire screen allows a hero to be hired. The statistics attached to each one has no explanation to what they are for resulting in either a lookup on the internet or just selecting randomly. Once a hero has been hired, they wander the town doing nothing unless they are actively on a quest. Once back from a quest they will be tired or injured. They must be selected on the main map screen and directed to the healing facilities. The hero management interface is broken and telling a hero to go heal from that screen results in the hero ignore the command. This is especially frustrating if there are many civilians exploring the town since it is hard to find a particular hero in the crowd. However, the training options from the hero management work, so get them guns son.ItemsThere seems to be a nice collection of fun items to acquire over the course of a game. Some improve the city, some are equitable on heroes. Unfortunately some of the biggest game breaking bugs come from items. Certain city improvements (rugs and pots) can be used to improve vendors in the game. After making an improvement, the item doesn't disappear and can be reused multiple times. After nearly five minutes upgrading all the vendors millions of gold were added to the treasury every time anything was purchased. Once the upgrades to the city were finished, any items left in the inventory were missing."
