,Recommended,314240,16770616,"Posted: 28 June, 2015",all,Trip Fisk,"tl;dr version: game still in alpha (incomplete, buggy), but now in an acceptable state as far as early access games go.edit 10/17/15 review updateWhen I first got RPG Tycoon many moons ago, it was just awful. One of those early access games so early in development, it felt like a gyp. It was like that for quite some time up until roughly the second half of 2015. That's when the developer finally got serious working on his game. I've seen RPG Tycoon grow and mature over time to a point where it is now showing promise and potential to be a decent albiet simple and crude management simulator.In my previous review, I  did not recommend due to how unstable it was and a memory leak that slowed the game down so much it became unplayable.Since then, those two issues are gone. I now recommend RPG Tycoon!Well, as an alpha anyway.RPG Tycoon is far from complete. Some features are still obviously being worked on. There are still annoying bugs you can't avoid while playing. Game is in need of balance tweaks. Loading save games still has a high risk of causing something to glitch out. Visitors still tend to get frozen in place and never leave.But the game is now in a state that I can call playable. Its pretty okay for what it is too.Basically if you've been eyeballing this game thinking about buying it, I'd say its safe to buy now. The developer is now supporting their game and updates are churning out more frequently. But, obviously, if you're one of those types who can't stand unfinished/buggy games steer clear for the time being. RPG Tycoon has a long way to go still."
76561198005376543,Recommended,314240,14664638,"Posted: 26 February, 2015",all,[SC.BO] Ninja,"This was my original review when the game was REALLLLLLY early in development:The game is currently way too incomplete to be any fun. I love this kind of games and some of the concepts are nice, but now there is simply not enough content and feature. If it ever eventually ships, it's worth considering. Right now, don't buy it, it's too empty.--Now, I've kinda changed my mind. RPG Tycoon has definitely reached the point where it's actually a full fledged game. You start with a very small patch of land on which you can build a couple of base buildings just to attract some adventurers to send questing. You slowly build up from there, trying to attract tourists from other Kingdoms. It's a game of progressive growth with some kingdom management and an interesting questing system based on guessing what are the correct combinations of supplies to bring while doing a specific activity (original yes, fun I don't know yet). All in all, a pretty likeable kingdom sim so why not, give it a try. Now it's worth it at its price range."
,Recommended,314240,11855839,"Posted: 24 August, 2014",all,Sunzo,"**********Updated 2/10/2015**********Below you'll see my previous reviews, I'm keeping them there as the review grows, so that any who are interested can see the progress made.Just like last time, I'll list off bugs first:1: Whenever two heroes rest in the same building, one of them will get locked in that building, and will never come out. the only way to get that hero back, is to sack them, watch their avatar leave the town and then rehire them.2: Various mispellings, if those even count as bugs.3: That's it, I haven't encountered any other bugs lately.Btw, for a TL;DR version, scroll to the bottom, just before the next updated line.So how is the game different now?Quick Quests now have a unique gameplay to them, that I haven't played in another tycoon game.First you select a town, then you select a quest type, after selecting that quest type, you have a screen of supplies, the supply screen is what I can assume the influences from Game Dev Tycoon turned into, and it adapts well.You see, each town requires different supplies on different quests, so even if you do a Raider quest in town A, and get all 6 supplies matched in their correct slots, that doesn't mean it'll be the same way in town B.You also do not get all the supplies straight off the bat, while I can't say I like having those supplies withheld, it makes for a lot of replayability as you try and earn all the supplies, so it ends up being pretty damn enjoyable.The Epic quests however feel lacking in comparison to the quick quests, and I think they could really utilise their own unique gameplay, I already see evidence of how this could be achieved with the mid quest story prompts, but I'd like to see something at the start, similar to quick quest's preparation stage, but unique.I don't understand the bounties very well at the moment, I searched for a villain and afterward that quest line became unaccessible.One of my major complaints in the previous versions was the lack of feedback, this has been corrected and there's now a lot of information on the screen, The hud can feel a bit encumbering, I'd like to either see the hud size be controllable in the options, but that wouldn't need to be an exact option, many other solutions would work.The top left window can be minimized but others can not. however, the bottom left one, shouldn't be able to be minimized, I'd rather see it fade into the background when a target isn't selected. I'd also like to see the bottom left window only function when a target is clicked instead of hovered over.The top right information feed, feels rather rough, the messages don't need to stay for long and could actually be automatically deleted for you, I'm sure though that the developer is looking at this, with his own solution in mind.The rest of the hud however, is well designed, pleasing to the eyes and gives relevant information.The research is good, but feels like it lacks a lot of research, and I'd like to see it play a second role.The town management is coming along nicely, and while playing, I actually thought that it was possible to create a self sustaining town, that does not rely on the funds from your heroes.I would like to see that be a thing, a self sustaining town, but I'd rather see it as a possible avenue for development in the game that you have to specifically pursue, and not an eventuality that every playthrough will lead to.TL;DR:The game is now at a playable stage, and the game finally has a strong foundation to fall back on, that doesn't take too heavily from other games.It's enjoyable, and in the playthrough that lead to this updated review, I actually sunk a few hours into it all at once.Rating:What it is: 6.5/10What it could be: 9/10I'm excited to see the end product when it leaves early access, I believe it'd net a 7.5/10 at this rate.********Updated 18/03/2015********First off, a lot of my old points are still rather relevant, the game hasn't terribly improved, and still stands as one of the more broken Early Access games I've played.First to the bugs:I haven't encountered any of the old bugs, but now I've met some of the new ones, one of them is map scrolling, if you roll your cursor to the edge, it scrolls, simple, lots of games have that, but some times when you roll your cursor to one of the edges, it doesn't scroll the map, and you have to jiggle the cursor at the right side of the screen to free it up.Then there's the auto continue, whenever a message pops up, something in the game will happen for example: auto save and the game will continue without me, while I read, the messages are quite length in this game too, so that creates a problem.Finally autosaving also flashes the screen, which is insanely annoying.The developer has steered away from it's Game Dev Tycoon inspired system, however it's current system isn't very interesting, and is still rather cryptic, because you don't get enough feedback after a quest as to why you got a bad rating, and some times the messages get repeated meaning what could have been a useful third message gets pushed off the table by a message I've already read.The game still isn't very interesting, and often puts me asleep, Still not a fan of the art direction, and the gameplay is lacking.At this time, I do not recommend this game.4/10 for the game as is.8/10 for the potential game, that I hope it one day becomes.******First Version******First off, I have to quickly explain:No, I do not hate this game, I actually really really like it and it's concept.The recommendation is in reference to it's playability in the current build.With that out of the way.RPG Tycoon scratches an itch that I love, Management games, I've had a thing for them since I played Rollercoaster Tycoon 2.So the ability to create my own RPG town, send heroes on quests and promote my town sounds like a heavenly game to me.But RPG Tycoon is still in early access, the major reason I do not recommend it is bugs, the game is at this current stage full of bugs and glitches, which is not surprising with an Early Access game, that's just early access for you, the developers are still making the game, bugs and glitches are to be expected, But at this time due to some game breaking bugs I can't recommend it.These bugs include (but are only limited to what I've seen thus far)-Duplicating heroes-Time pausing days not progressing but quests remaining open and progressing without reaching a climax.-Saving and Loading does not take the game back to before the bugs occured (not a bug, but is annoying when trying to avoid bugs)And with that part out of the way, here is the rest of my thoughts:The concept is great, I can't wait to see this in a playable state.The graphic style itself I can't say I'm a fan of, I'd like it to be different, but at the same time, it doesn't matter, I'll happily ignore that.The Game Dev Tycoon type of direction with quests is both familiar and inviting, making me wish to try the same quest multiple times, however I feel there needs to be a way to investigate these quests to get hints at what are the right and wrong choices.The music is excellent, it reminds me of minecraft but not in a way that feels bland and unoriginal, the music feels like a winner.Add in random events to the final release? that would be amazing.I can't wait to see the potential for large towns with sprawlling citizens and several different buildings like blacksmith, tailor and what not.I'd like to also request a micromanagement system with the citizens, giving them jobs I mean, and having them live within your city.I have so many high hopes for this game, and I can't wait until it's in a more playable state so I can sit down for a good while and play it.Buy it? please do! the more purchases the more funding, the more funding the quick and better the progression."
